rtant to understand that this is a very' b'different problem from the image format conversions in item converting' b'one image format to another is a fairly easy problem, since once you' b'get past all the file header junk, a pixel is a pixel the basic objects' b'are the same for all image formats. this is not so for vector formats.' b'the basic objects circles, ellipses, drop-shadowed pattern-filled' b'round-cornered rectangles, etc. vary from one format to another.' b'except in extremely restricted cases, it is simply not possible to do' b'a one-to-one conversion between vector formats.' b'' b'there is software for converting to and from cgm files on ftp.psc.edu. the' b'contributor states that it runs on unix, ms-windows, and possibly the mac.' b'a better, more specific blurb would be most welcome.' b'' b'on the other hand, it is quite possible to do a close approximation,' b'rendering an image from one format using the primitives from another.' b'as far as i know, no one has put together a general toolkit of such' b'converters, but two different hpgl to postscript converters have been' b'posted to comp.sources.misc. check the index on your nearest archive' b'site.' b'' b'a related frequent question is how to convert from some vector format' b'to a bitmapped image from postscript to sun raster format, or hpgl to' b'x11 bitmap. for example, some of the commercial postscript clones for' b"pc's allow you to render to a disk file as well as a printer. also," b"the postscript interpreters in the next box and in sun's x11/news can" b"be used to render to a file if you're clever. but in general, the" b'answer is no. however, if someone were to put together a vector to' b'vector conversion toolkit, adding a vector to raster converter would be' b'trivial.' b'' b'gnu ghostscript (from the fsf current version includes' b'drivers for both ppm and gif format files, thus it can be used as' b'a postscript to ppm or a postscript to gif filter. (it implements' b'essentially all of postscript level and alot of display postscript' b'and level b'' b'' b'10) how to get pixar films.' b'' b'the various john lasseter pixar computer animated shorts are available' b'on video tape. you can order them from direct cinema limited:' b'' b'film individual price institutional price' b'luxo, jr.\t\t\t\t$14.95\t\t\t$50.00' b"red's dream\t\t\t\t$19.95\t\t\t$75.00" b'tin toy\t\t\t\t$24.95\t\t\t$75.00' b'knickknack\t\t\t\t$24.95\t\t\t$75.00' b"luxo, jr./red's dream/tin toy\t$39.95\t\t\t$100.00" b'' b'all tapes are on vhs ntsc. add $10/tape for pal format. also' b'available:' b'' b'tin toy t-shirt\t\t\t$15.00' b'knickknack 3d t-shirt\t\t$15.00 (includes glasses)' b'' b'for individual orders, add s&h for the first tape or shirt, for' b'each additional tape or shirt. for institutional orders, add s&h' b'for the first tape, for each additional tape. foreign shipping, add' b'$3/tape or shirt. call international,' b'213-396-3233 fax) to charge to your credit card. call first to verify' b'prices and availability. or, just write to:' b'' b'direct cinema limited' b'1749 14th street' b'santa monica, ca b'' b'allan braunsdorf has this to say:' b'' b'at siggraph they were selling a tape with all four shorts' b'for that was a sale price. you can get it for slightly' b"more than that normally. maybe.) i believe it's" b"available from renderman retail (at pixar's address)." b'' b'pixar' b'1001 west cutting blvd.' b'richmond, ca. b'(510) b'(510) (fax)' b'' b'you can obtain a video directly from pixar which contains "luxo, jr.", "red\'s' b'dream", "tin toy" and "knicknack" for plus for shipping. they' b'will take your order over the phone or via fax with a major credit card. i' b"ordered mine just last week and received it several days later. don't expect" b'to be able to rent a copy from your local video store. according to the license' b'agreement printed on the back cover of the case, it cannot be rented.' b'' b'' b'11) how do i draw a circle as a bezier (or b-spline) curve?' b'' b'the short answer is, "you can\'t." unless you use a rational spline you' b'can only approximate a circle. the approximation may look acceptable,' b'but it is sensitive to scale. magnify the scale and the error of' b'approximation magnifies. deviations from circularity that were not' b'visible in the small can become glaring in the large. if you want to' b'do the job right, consult the article:' b'' b'"a menagerie of rational b-spline circles"' b'by leslie piegl and wayne tiller' b'in ieee computer graphics and applications, volume number b'september, pages b'' b'for rough, non-rational approximations, consult the book:' b'' b'computational geometry for design and manufacture' b'by i. d. faux and m. j. pratt,' b'ellis horwood publishers, halsted press, john wiley b'' b'for the best known non-rational approximations, consult the article:' b'' b'"good approximation of circles by curvature-continuous bezier curves"' b'by tor dokken, morten daehlen, tom lyche, and knut morken' b'in computer aided geometric design, volume numbers (combined),' b'june, pages [elsevier science publishers (north-holland)]' b'' b'' b'12) how to order standards documents.' b'' b'the american national standards institute sells ansi standards, and also' b'iso (international) standards. their sales office is at b'mailing address is broadway, ny ny it helps if you have the' b'complete name and number.' b'' b'some useful numbers to know:' b'' b'cgm (computer graphics metafile) is iso gks (graphical' b"kernel system) is ansi x3.124-1985. phigs (programmer's hierarchical" b'interactive graphics system) is ansi x3.144-1988. iges is asme/ansi' b'y14.26m-1987. language bindings are often separate but related numbers;' b'for example, the gks fortran binding is x3.124.1-1985.' b'' b'standards-in-progress are made available at key milestones to solicit' b'comments from the graphical public (this includes you!). ansi can let' b'you know where to order them; most are available from global engineering' b'at b'' b'' b'13) how to ftp by email.' b'' b'there are a number of sites that archive the usenet sources newsgroups' b'and make them available via an email query system. you send a message' b'to an automated server saying something like "send comp.sources.unix/fbm",' b'and a few hours or days later you get the file in the mail.' b'' b'in addition, there is at least one ftp-by-mail server. send mail to' b'it. note that this service has at times been turned off due to abuse.' b'' b'' b'14) how to tell whether a point is within a planar polygon.' b'' b'consider a ray originating at the point of interest and continuing to' b'infinity. if it crosses an odd number of polygon edges along the way,' b'the point is within the polygon. if the ray crosses an even number of' b'edges, the point is either outside the polygon, or within an interior' b'hole formed from intersecting polygon edges. this idea is known in' b"the trade as the jordan curve theorem; see eric haines' article in" b"glassner's ray tracing book (above) for more information, including" b'treatment of special cases.' b'' b'another method is to sum the absolute angles from the point to all' b'the vertices on the polygon. if the sum is pi, the point is inside,' b'if the sum is the point is outside. however, this method is about an' b'order of magnitude slower than the previous method because evaluating the' b'trigonometric functions is usually quite costly.' b'' b'code for both methods (plus barycentric triangle testing) can be found in' b'the ray tracing news, vol. no. available from princeton.edu:' b'pub/graphics/rtnews/rtnv5n3.z.' b'' b'' b'15) how to tessellate a sphere.' b'' b'one simple way is to do recursive subdivision into triangles. the' b'base of the recursion is an octahedron, and then each level divides' b'has posted a nice routine called sphere.c that generates the coordinates.' b"it's available for ftp on ftp.ee.lbl.gov and princeton.edu." b'' b'16) specific references on ray-tracing and global illumination.' b'' b'rick speer maintains a cross-indexed ray-tracing bibliography:' b'' b'highlights of this edition-' b'' b'i) more than citations spanning the period from through' b"november b'ii) papers from all siggraph, graphics interface, eurographics, cg' b"international and ausgraph proceedings through december, b'iii) all citations keyworded for easy lookup;' b'iv) cross-indices by keyword and author;' b'v) glossary of the keywords used.' b'' b'the bib is in the form of a postscript file. the printout is pages long.' b"below is a list of ftp sites and the dirs that contain the file. it's named" b'"speer.raytrace.bib.ps.z" and is compressed at most sites-' b'' b'site dir' b'wuarchive.wustl.edu\tgraphics/graphics/bib/rt.bib.speer/' b'karazm.math.uh.edu\tpub/graphics/' b'gondwana.ecr.mu.oz.au\tpub/papers/' b'nic.funet.fi\t\tpub/sci/papers/graphics' b'coral.cs.jcu.edu.au graphics/papers/' b'' b'illumination bibliographies. these are in "refer" format, and so can be' b'searched electronically (a simple awk script to search for keywords is' b'included with each). the bibliographies are available at most of the' b'sites listed above, and the most current versions are maintained at' b'princeton.edu: pub/graphics/papers as "raybib.*" and "radbib.*".' b'' b'tracing related research papers and books. the information is essentially' b'in plaintext, and latex and troff formatting programs are included. this' b'collection is available at most of the sites above as "rtabs.*".' b'' b'17) siggraph information online' b'' b'[from steve cunningham and ralph orlick]' b'' b'acm-siggraph announces its online information site at siggraph.org' b'(128.248.245.250). this site now provides siggraph information via both' b'anonymous ftp and an electronic mail archive server.' b'' b'the anonymous ftp service is very standard, and the ftp directory includes' b'both conference and publications subdirectories.' b'' b'to retrieve information by electronic mail, send mail to' b'and in the subject or the body of the message include the message send' b'followed by the topic and subtopic you wish. a good place to start is with' b'the command' b'send index' b'which will give you an up-to-date list of available information.' b'' b'' b'18) siggraph panels proceedings available' b'' b'[from steve cunningham and bob judd]' b'' b"acm siggraph announces the availability of the siggraph panels proceedings" b'at the siggraph.org site the proceedings are available' b'in three formats:' b'text (ascii)' b'rtf (rich text format, suitable for many word processors)' b'word (ms word for the macintosh)' b'they may be retrieved from siggraph.org in two ways:' b'' b'(1) by anonymous ftp' b'change to one of the directories' b'publications/s91/panels_proceedings/[text|rtf|word]' b'the text and rtf files may be downloaded in ascii mode, while the word' b'files are stored in macbinary format and must be downloaded in binary' b'mode.' b'' b'each directory contains a table of contents file (toc) that describes the' b'contents of each panel file.' b'' b'(2) by electronic mail' b'send mail to' b'you can retrieve either the text or rtf files. we suggest that you' b'first retrieve the index files by putting one of the messages' b'send panel91-txt index' b'send panel91-rtf index' b'in the subject or body of the message. you will get the necessary' b'information to retrieve the actual transcript files.' b'' b'' b'19) graphics mailing lists' b'' b'there are a variety of graphics-related mailing list out there, each' b'covering either a single product or a single topic. i have been an' b'active participant in one of these for some time now, and find the' b'focus and expertise which can be brought to bear on an isolated topic' b'to be nothing short of amazing.' b'' b'please send me the appropriate information if you have any others you' b'would like to see added.' b'' b'name:\t\timagine mailing list' b'description:\tdiscussion forum for users of the imagine 3d rendering and' b'animation p